               <img alt="" class="wide-image" data-attrs='{"src":"https://bucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/5a602d67-0688-45b3-96de-a820c93eb75f_828x337.png","height":337,"width":828,"resizeWidth":552,"bytes":null,"alt":null,"title":null,"type":null,"href":null}' src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1104,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F5a602d67-0688-45b3-96de-a820c93eb75f_828x337.png" style="-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic; border: none !important; display: block; height: auto; margin: 0 auto; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 550px; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;" width="550"/>
              </a>
             </td>
             <td style="text-align: center;">
             </td>
            </tr>
           </tbody>
          </table>
         </figure>
        </div>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Depending on how you look at it, that\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9cdemocratizing options trading\xe2\x80\x9d or making it way too easy so Robinhood can make money.
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          How Robinhood Makes Money
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cShow me the incentive and I\xe2\x80\x99ll show you the outcome.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Robinhood is clearly incentivized to get its users to take on risk; last week\xe2\x80\x99s outcome was inevitable.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Robinhood designed its product to encourage and facilitate margin and options trading, because that\xe2\x80\x99s how Robinhood gets paid. It makes money in
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAQRE8z7MYCDLZnwSKbXMPC0LbRmI_4JPHt0zOWEoQKUKm6xDO6whbzqVIslbxkrmcCFeC7HFArZNIK5NlZxQY-9VI8iFXCsklOxJV5zQBeu0PV3ICkthzO6OpieCco5ZLsShszDYMeQNuRjxOsveDrKgSFh6GrfFy9ulkHwYCCL8hnDEAOtdeayq3_uPFP3DkuLuwx2s5Ej-9WUCCglJZSzBVvOldnDng5e_y-_0XuXj-h3D3OPdEjTnHKGeWUsV7i6ljnl_STIIvUm5ugfuNdaUup2jxffSSrEOsSswsb2s9dezjeBv56xtO34Oo5Q9DLAfYCUi-ub0TzBgEy8razrkiTcTaNo5RcygsAEus5nfqRCoLNNmIq_Jf-ArJLkmQ" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          five ways
         </a>
         :
        </p>
        <ol style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Selling order flow to hedge funds (\xe2\x80\x9cpayment for order flow\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9cPFOF). They typically make more by selling options order flow than equities order flow.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Selling Robinhood Gold subscriptions for $5/month,
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Providing margin to customers at a 2.5% interest rate (down from 5%) in December.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Lending out securities to counter parties who want to short it.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Earning interest on cash balances.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Let\xe2\x80\x99s cover PFOF first, because it\xe2\x80\x99s one of the most controversial and misunderstood issues surrounding Robinhood.
         <strong>
          PFOF is not inherently bad, and most brokerages do it
         </strong>
         . Here are two fun bits of history, though:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Know who came up with the idea for PFOF?
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkUtuhDAMhk8zWaI8gVlk0U2vgfIwEJUkNISZcvsaWFSNLNty7N_RF2cqTLkces1bJacb6rGCTvDeFqgVCtk3KEPwmrW8F0o-idfSs171JGzDWACiCYuuZQey7nYJztSQ0zVBKVdk1q314FinnqO0lMHTC6Fo27dOecup9fdes_sAyYGGF5QjJyCLnmtdt4f4ePBPtDfYxhQ3hxc0uUx3BT2nnNKedYxLfB8W_o9F1Doal1LjcrzaKcVA1Zmf7SG9YKshnYrfQzQ-jyOmJGhUZijOmFB4GtZEu_6sUOQq3EPSOPFm2-1Wjfs6xUnRKVeby6kl6ddsIizXBZIZMMY9hXoMkIxdwN_Q6s3-wjhMkKDgn_jBVCTOOOu7Timu1A0JqQpOe9FRSXCzzziV_pb-AiDSmEM" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            Bernie Madoff.
           </a>
           Yup.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           Citadel, the largest buyer of Robinhood\xe2\x80\x99s flows,
           <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAMhk8TliMgOJMsWFSq5hoRDzeDmkAEptPcvmSyqISMLT9--3OGcEn50HsqxE4z07GjjvgqKxJhZrVgnoPXYpBjD2piXisvRhhZKPNXRtxMWDXlimyvdg3OUEjx3cG5BPbUIIR3fhIeJjlNYD0fB-sMKD8IsI5fuqb6gNGhxh_MR4rIVv0k2kvXf3Ty0R69wrnRzaWtRXapecWjeYUM1dIc0QNMwLlomw6TBKV41z_agE8pWNCSS8ElF2cZwE3cNrv_7pjV3rtO8W2Rt1Jtm-a-Tw2WdUxkUw5xaenvp9lwfSfanXP7txoDHTNGY1f0FwK6SL6hzAtGzI2wnw01fkKK8X4HkADXyY1RL_nY37liTdmn1hX_Rf8AGVqI7w" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
            wrote a letter to the SEC in 2004
           </a>
           arguing that PFOF should be banned. lol.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Additionally,
         <strong>
          Robinhood makes more money for selling its order flow than most brokerages
         </strong>
         .
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkM1uxCAMhJ9mOUb8hIQcOPSyr4EIOAnaBBA4bfP2pZtDVcuyD6PR6BtnEdZULp1TRfJ7DF4ZdISvugMiFHJWKCZ4zQauhOwn4nXvmZKKhGqWAnDYsGssJ5B8zntwFkOKbwelXJJNz8MyCGmpnZSaYPGM22HsRz5Qy0YrpjvXnj5AdKDhE8qVIpBdb4i5PsTHgz_bLiEiuA2Tt1dXz7mida_OpaNpJGhOOaOcMiZkm451x5y_M5Q-C_fo6bHyfyZSdEw4pxLi2uTXZg_Y30LDMO0fZwx4GYh23sHfhHgX9WY2K0QorUBvLLZ6GGdqHKXkUt5ErQLBqRIj7UlL9qm54l_oD1YkgVY" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          FinTech Today
         </a>
         asked some experts why that is back in July, and the answer comes down to three things:
        </p>
        <ol style="margin: 1em 0;">
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           The type of trader on Robinhood: easy for funds to assume they\xe2\x80\x99re all unsophisticated given the simplicity of the interface, whereas it\xe2\x80\x99s harder to tell on other platforms.
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           What they trade: a ton of options, many with wide bid-ask spreads
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin: 3.75px 0 3.75px 7.5px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;">
           How Robinhood charges: a % of the spread vs. a fixed fee for most brokerages.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuOwyAQRE8TlhbfQBYsZjPXsPi0HRQbEG5PxrcfHC8GIVqoVKp-FRzCXNpha9mQnM-IRwWb4b0tgAiN7Bu0MUXL7twIJR8kWhmZUYakbZwawOrSYrHtQOrulxQcppI_Dkq5Ik_LpWbGCfPwMMkpTELEqLnW9wDgJ-quXLfHBDmAhR9oR8lAFvtErNtNfN34d7_4TudGQyhr_3nIuUKaoCFJllPOKKeMCdXPwIbV198KTVYRbpKuMx-23W_owuv0k2ZzQV9aynOXX0-3wvIROsPY57rnhMcI2fkF4oWHV0sf4HGGDK23F0eHvRvGmdFaKa7UhdP5BadGaCpJT46lu_J_6B_IDYFe" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Benn Eifert
         </a>
         put it succinctly: \xe2\x80\x9cThe profitability of order flow determines its pricing power. The product is the user, and high volume of non-toxic (uninformed) order flow in high spread options trades is highly profitable.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Saying Robinhood traders are unsophisticated isn\xe2\x80\x99t mean; it\xe2\x80\x99s facts.
         <strong>
          The market puts a price on how bad the trading on each platform is, and it pays Robinhood more than anyone else.
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The fact is, value judgments aside, the company is clearly incentivized to get people to trade more often, to trade more options, and to trade on margin.
         <strong>
          The ideal trader on Robinhood, from a revenue perspective, is a Robinhood Gold subscriber who frequently trades options on margin
         </strong>
         . That also happens to be the riskiest kind of trading behavior for the individual traders themselves.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         When things go wrong, which they inevitably do, and someone criticizes Robinhood, the company hides behind the guise of democratizing access to the markets, saying something like:
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           It\xe2\x80\x99s a free market! They\xe2\x80\x99re adults! Are you saying they aren\xe2\x80\x99t entitled to the same wealth creation opportunities as the big fancy hedge funds just because they weren\xe2\x80\x99t born rich? We\xe2\x80\x99re on the side of the little guy! Whose side are YOU on anyway? Elite\xe2\x80\xa6
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         This is Silicon Valley 101. It
         <em>
          feels
         </em>
         wrong, using slick and disingenuous marketing to obscure misaligned incentives, but all of the big tech companies do some version of this. As long as it operates within the legal and regulatory bounds, though, Robinhood is able, and even fiduciarily obligated, to do whatever it takes to maximize shareholder value.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But, as last week showed, Robinhood is also subject to the savagery of the market. It can\xe2\x80\x99t externalize all of the real risk it generates with words alone.
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          Robinhood, WSB, and Entropy Theory
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In 2013, two Stanford grads, Baiju Bhatt and Vlad Tenev, founded Robinhood, based, so
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMuOgzAM_JrmiJKQAD3ksJf-BsrDhah5KRi6_P2m5bCWZVu2xqMZqxGWXE9V8obkU2Y8C6gE7y0AIlSyb1Bn7xQb-NRLcSdOCccmORG_zc8KELUPCusOpOwmeKvR5_RFUMolWdXdiaeV91GMBvQg-WC1dOMgR9FTY6S4ePXuPCQLCg6oZ05AgloRy3brf2780RJXwDckPKNPO8JhO5tj2x9BO4QER5uJV5xyRjllrJctOtZFU34LVFF6exM0LrzbdrOhtq_PA1JVymhy9Wlp59eqI4TvocmZW4978njOkLQJ4C6leBn21T4vjbs2I92ssdnEOJvGUUou5aWsWdFzOvUjFaQxu9xQ6Z_0DwOWhLk" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          the story
         </a>
         goes, on two simultaneous events: Occupy Wall Street and the rise of mobile. They set out to build a mobile commission-free trading app that \xe2\x80\x9cuntethered the financial markets from the typical computer setup with multiple monitors.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Between 2013 and 2017, Robinhood was a typical Silicon Valley startup. It used technology to make trading easy, and introduced innovations like commission-free trading and fractional shares, which genuinely democratized access to investing.
        </p>
